The disease immediately left him. He recovered.
Jesus sent him away immediately. And he gave the man a stern warning.
"Do not say this to anyone," he said. "Go and show yourself to the priest. Offer the sacrifices commanded by Moses. This will be evidence to the priest and the people that you are 'clean'."
But the man went out and began to proclaim it freely and to spread the news, so that Jesus could no longer enter a town openly. He remained in secluded places, but people still came to him from everywhere.
Jesus heals a man who cannot walk.
A few days later, Jesus again entered Capernaum, and the people heard that he had come home.
A great multitude gathered together, so that there was no room, not even outside the door. And Jesus preached the word to them.
Four of the arrivals were carrying a man who couldn't walk.
But they could not get near Jesus because of the crowd. So they made an opening in the roof above Jesus and, after digging out the tiles, they lowered the mat on which the paralyzed man was lying.
Jesus saw their faith. He said to the man, "Child, your sins are forgiven."
Some law professors were sitting there. They were thinking.
"Why is this person like this? He says such evil things! But God forgives sins!"
Jesus knew their thoughts and said to them, "Why are you thinking these things in your hearts?"
Is it easier to say to this man, "Your sins are forgiven you"? Or to say, "Rise, take up your bed and walk"?
"I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then Jesus spoke to the man who couldn't walk.
"I tell you," he said, "get up. Take your prayer mat and go home."
The man rose and took up his mat. Then he walked away, while everyone watched. They were all amazed. They praised God and said, "We have never seen anything like this before!" Jesus chooses Levi.
Jesus went out again beside the Sea of Galilee. A large crowd came to him. He began to teach them.
As Jesus walked along, he saw Levi son of Alphaeus sitting at the tax collectors booth. Follow me, he told him, and Levi got up and followed him.
Then Jesus ate dinner at Levi's house. Many tax collectors and "sinners" were eating with him and his disciples. They were part of the large crowd that was following Jesus.
There were some teachers of the law who were Pharisees. They saw Jesus eating with "sinners" and tax collectors. So they asked his disciples, "Why does he eat with tax collectors and 'sinners'?"
Jesus heard this and said to them, "It is not those who are healthy who need a doctor, but those who are sick. I did not come to call the righteous, but sinners, to repentance." Jesus asks about fasting.
The disciples of John and the Pharisees were fasting. Some people came to Jesus and said to him, "The disciples of John fast, and the disciples of the Pharisees fast, but yours do not. Why do they not fast?"
Jesus answered, "How can the guests of the bridegroom fast while the bridegroom is with them? The time will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them, and then they will fast."
But the time will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them. On that day they will fast.
People do not sew a new piece of cloth onto old clothes. If they do, the new piece will tear away from the old one. That will only make the tear worse.
People do not pour new wine into old wine skins. If they do, the wine will burst the skins. Then both the wine and the skins will be destroyed. No, they pour new wine into new wine skins. Jesus is Lord of the Sabbath.
On one of the sabbath days, Jesus was walking through wheatfields with his disciples. And the disciples began to pluck some of the heads of grain.
The Pharisees said to Jesus, "Look, your disciples are doing what is unlawful on the Sabbath."
He replied, "Have you never read what David did? He and his men were hungry. They needed food.
That was in the days of Abiathar the high priest. David went into the house of God, and ate the shewbread, which was lawful only for the priests to eat. And he gave also to his companions.
Then Jesus said to them, "The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath."
"Therefore the Son of Man is Lord even of the Sabbath day."
Healing on Saturday
At another time Jesus entered the temple. There was a man with a withered and distorted hand.
Some Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They were watching him closely. They wanted to see if he would heal the man on the Sabbath.
Jesus spoke to the man who had a withered and paralyzed hand. He said to him, "Stand up before everyone."
Then Jesus said to them, "What does the law say we should do on the Sabbath? Make it a day for good deeds or for evil? To save life or to destroy it?" But they remained silent.
Jesus looked at them with anger. He was very angry because their hearts were hard. Then he said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." He stretched out his hand, and his hand was restored as good as new.
Then the Pharisees went out and began to plot with the Herodians against Jesus, how they might kill Him. Multitudes were following Jesus.
Jesus went with his disciples to the Sea of Galilee. Large crowds from Galilee followed him.
The people heard all that Jesus was doing. And many came to him, from Judea, Jerusalem, and all the surrounding regions, including Idumea, beyond the Jordan, and around Tyre and Sidon.
Because of the crowd, Jesus asked his disciples to prepare a small boat for him. This would protect the people from crowding around him.
Jesus healed many people. Therefore, the sick were pushing forward to touch him.
When the people who had evil spirits saw Jesus, they fell on their faces and worshiped Him. The spirits cried out, "You are the Son of God!"
But Jesus commanded them not to tell who he was. Jesus appoints the twelve apostles.
Jesus went up a mountain. He called some people to come to him, and they came.
And he appointed twelve, whom he also named apostles, that they might be with him and that he might send them out to preach.
They will have authority to cast out demons.
So Jesus appointed twelve, and among them was Simon, to whom he gave the name Peter.
There were Jacob, son of Zebedee, and his brother John. Jesus gave them the name Boanerges, which means Sons of Thunder.
And Andrew, and Philip, and Bartholomew, and Matthew, and Thomas, and James the son of Alphaeus. Also, Thaddaeus and Simon the Zealot.
Judas Iscariot was one of them. He was the one who would later betray Jesus into the hands of his enemies. Jesus and Beelzebub
Jesus entered a house. Another crowd gathered. The crowd was so large that Jesus and his disciples could not eat.
His family heard about it. So they went to take care of him. They said, "He has gone mad."
There were some scribes. They came down from Jerusalem. They said, "He is under the authority of Beelzebul! He casts out demons by the power of the prince of demons!"
So Jesus said to them, "How can Satan drive out Satan?"
If a kingdom fights itself, it will not stand.
If the family is divided, it will not stand.
